00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:04.820
The Paranormal Activity movies, despite the stories and characters becoming less developed

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:07.820
do still offer new ways of scaring people

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:11.100
Yeah, we get those fake out jumpscares that are always awful, but

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:16.100
then there are ideas like the camera going back and forth slowly revealing the scare

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:20.320
or literally dangling a knife off-screen never knowing when it's going to fall

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:25.500
or even just moving spots, f**king MOVING SPOTS can suddenly become terrifying

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:30.240
It's this kind of simplicity that can get the biggest frights with the subtlest of actions

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:35.320
One of my favourite edits is in Paranormal Activity 2, when the daughter thinks something has taken over her mother

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:37.980
We get a scene of the mother about to confront her in her room

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:41.280
and then we just cut to the daughter crying on the phone asking for help

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:47.800
We have no idea what happened in between but our imagination is much more disturbing than anything it could have shown

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:54.200
And seeing how a lot of found footage is very much less is more, it allows clever touches like that to shine the best

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:57.640
When it has to work through the limitations by being clever

00:04:58.020 --> 00:05:01.880
It's like shooting an entire movie in a coffin, or a whole film on a chairlift

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.780
When you take away the usual distractions, it allows you to focus more on the meat of the story

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.360
and it can only be done well by truly smart film makers

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:14.600
But with that said, a lot of times the style can be the distraction

00:05:15.140 --> 00:05:20.800
The master of zombie films, George A. Romero took his stab at the found footage style and failed miserably

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:23.600
Nothing ever looked like actual found footage

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:28.360
It was too well shot, too nice sounding and too much acted like a Hollywood film

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:32.560
Something like this makes you realise not only is there a right way to do found footage,

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:35.400
but there's a logical reason for why it can work

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:38.400
What do horror movies, as well as most movies try to do?

00:05:38.400 --> 00:05:41.020
They try to make you feel like you're in the films

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:43.300
so you can identify more with the situation

00:05:43.360 --> 00:05:45.800
But where most movies need to film a main character,

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.920
with found footage the main character is the one that's filming

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:52.440
so it's much easier to make you feel like you're the one in the situation

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:55.620
When it works, it can get some of the biggest scares you can imagine

00:05:56.700 --> 00:06:00.740
But the downside is, people are much more critical and rightfully so

00:06:01.380 --> 00:06:04.380
Not believing the environment or characters in a found footage movie

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:08.480
is ten times worse than if you don't believe it in any other genre

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:11.940
because the whole point is to make you feel like you're really there

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:16.780
and if the story, characters or acting are so far fetched that it knocks you out of that illusion

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:18.100
the film falls apart

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:21.420
The majority of the Paranormal Activity movies have good scares

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:23.940
but because they had to make them so fast...

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:24.760
(one every year)

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:29.620
